initial_story:
The National Police Air Service has shared a video of what it was like flying through Storm Gerrit's heavy winds, in a helicopter.

The footage, which was captured from inside the cockpit, shows the chopper rocking side to side, after being hit by winds of up to 80mph (128km/h).

Posting on X, formerly known as Twitter, the NPAS said "If you think it's windy down there, spare a thought for us up here in our flying washing machine".

The footage was filmed near Lea Valley reservoirs, North London.
stories: The helicopter, a Eurocopter EC135, was on a routine patrol mission when it encountered the severe weather conditions.
As the pilot struggled to maintain control, the helicopter was buffeted by strong winds and heavy rain, making it difficult to see more than a few feet in front of him.

The instruments on the dashboard were shaking violently, making it hard to read the vital signs, and the pilot's heart was racing with every jolt and lurch of the helicopter. Suddenly, a loud crack of thunder boomed outside, making him jump in his seat, and he felt a surge of adrenaline course through his veins.

As he regained his composure, he glanced out the window to see a torrent of rain pouring down, reducing visibility to almost zero. The helicopter was being tossed about like a toy, and he knew they were in for a bumpy ride. He gripped the controls tightly, his knuckles white with tension, and focused on navigating through the storm.

The instruments on the dashboard were shaking violently, making it difficult to read the gauges, and the rotor blades were creaking and groaning under the strain of the turbulent air. Suddenly, the helicopter lurched violently to the left, throwing him off balance, and he had to fight to regain control.

His hands were slick with sweat as he struggled to adjust the cyclic stick, trying to compensate for the sudden movement, but the helicopter seemed to have a mind of its own, bucking and twisting in ways that defied logic.

The rotors screamed in protest as he fought to regain control, the G-forces pressing him deep into the worn leather seat, his vision blurring at the edges as the landscape outside became a green and brown blur.

The altimeter was spinning wildly, the needle trembling as the plane bucked and lurched, threatening to send him careening into the trees below, and he gritted his teeth, his eyes fixed on the horizon as he struggled to level out, the roar of the engines growing louder, more menacing, as the ground rushed up to meet him.

His hands were slick with sweat, his fingers trembling on the controls as he fought to regain control, the plane shuddering and rattling like a leaf in a hurricane, the trees looming closer and closer, their branches reaching out like skeletal fingers to snatch him down, and he could feel his heart racing in his chest, pounding out a frantic rhythm that seemed to match the pounding of the engines, the wind whipping through his hair, his face set in a grimace of concentration as he wrestled the plane back under control.

The instruments on the dashboard were a blur, the needles quivering wildly as he struggled to keep the plane level, the altimeter spinning wildly as he plummeted towards the earth, the trees now mere feet away, their branches scraping against the fuselage with a sickening screech, and he could feel the G-force pushing him deep into his seat, his vision blurring at the edges as he fought to stay conscious, the roar of the engines deafening, the wind a constant scream in his ears, and he knew that if he didn't get it under control soon, they would all be crashing to their deaths in a fiery ball of wreckage.

His hands were slick with sweat, his fingers trembling as he grasped the controls, his eyes darting wildly between the instruments, searching for some glimmer of hope, some way to right the plane, but it was like trying to steer a runaway train, the momentum too great, the plane too heavy, and he could feel the panic rising up in his chest, his breath coming in ragged gasps, his mind racing with thoughts of his wife, his children, his friends, all of them counting on him to get them out of this alive, and he knew that if he failed, he would never forgive himself, the thought driving him to dig deep, to find the strength to push through the fear, to fight for every second, every inch of altitude, every breath of life.

His knuckles white with tension, he gripped the controls tighter, his gaze fixed on the horizon as he struggled to level out the plane, the G-force pressing him back into his seat, his vision blurring at the edges, but he refused to give in, his mind screaming at him to stay focused, to think, to find a way out of this nightmare, his thoughts a jumble of memories and prayers, his heart pounding in his chest like a drum, the sound of his own ragged breathing the only thing that broke the silence, and yet, despite the chaos, he felt a strange sense of clarity, a sense of purpose, a sense that he was exactly where he was meant to be, fighting for his life, fighting for the lives of those he loved.

The engines roared back to life, the plane shuddering beneath him as he fought to regain control, the altimeter spinning wildly as he plummeted towards the earth, his mind racing with the thought of the impact, the flames, the screams, and yet, even as the darkness closed in, he felt a spark of determination ignite within him, a flame that burned brighter with every passing moment, illuminating the path ahead, guiding him through the storm, and with a fierce cry, he yanked the controls hard to the left, the plane responding sluggishly, but responding nonetheless, as he banked sharply, the G-force pushing him deep into his seat, the world outside a blur of blue and green, the horizon a distant memory, and he knew, in that instant, that he was going to make it, that he was going to ride this beast to safety, no matter what the cost.

The sweat dripped from his brow, stinging his eyes as he struggled to keep his gaze fixed on the horizon, the plane shuddering and bucking beneath him like a wild animal, the roar of the engines a deafening cacophony that threatened to consume him whole, and yet, he held fast, his grip on the controls like a vice, his heart pounding in his chest like a drum, as he wrestled the plane back under control, the landscape below a chaotic blur of trees and buildings, the wind a screaming vortex that threatened to rip the wings from his back, and still, he fought on, his determination burning brighter with every passing moment, a beacon of hope in the darkness, guiding him through the storm, towards the safety of the runway, where he knew, in his heart, he would emerge victorious, battered and bruised, but alive.

As the plane finally began to stabilize, he felt a surge of relief wash over him, his grip on the controls relaxing ever so slightly, his eyes scanning the instruments with a newfound sense of calm, the roar of the engines still deafening, but no longer overwhelming, the landscape below slowly coming into focus, the trees and buildings resolving into a familiar pattern, the runway lights shining like a beacon in the distance, guiding him home, his heart still racing, but his mind clear, his focus fixed on the task at hand, as he gently guided the plane down, down, down, towards the safety of the ground, the wind still howling, but no longer a threat, the plane's engines dying down, the silence that followed a welcome respite, as he brought the plane to a stop, the wheels screeching on the pavement, the sound of the engines dying away, leaving only the sound of his own ragged breathing, and the quiet, steady hum of the plane's systems, as he sat there, frozen, his eyes fixed on the instruments, his mind reeling with the aftermath of the storm, his body trembling with exhaustion, but his spirit unbroken, his heart still beating strong.

As he sat there, the silence was oppressive, heavy with the weight of the storm's aftermath. As he relived the horror of that day, he could almost smell the acrid scent of burning rubber and feel the icy grip of fear that had taken hold of his heart, making his hands tremble as he grasped the controls. The memories came flooding back, a jumbled mix of sounds and images that threatened to consume him whole. He recalled the panicked screams of the passengers, the frantic beeping of the alarm system, and the eerie silence that followed as the plane plummeted towards the earth.

The faces of the people he had tried to save flashed before his eyes, their eyes wide with fear as they grasped for anything to hold onto, anything to keep them from falling. He remembered the feeling of weightlessness, the sensation of his stomach dropping as the plane's descent became a freefall. And then, the impact, the crushing force of the crash that had left him dazed and disoriented, unsure of what was happening or what lay ahead.

As he struggled to clear the haze from his mind, he became aware of the sounds around him - the groaning of twisted metal, the cries of the injured, and the eerie silence that followed. He tried to sit up, but a searing pain shot through his head, forcing him back onto the cold, hard ground. The faces of the dead and the dying swirled in his mind, their eyes still wide with fear, their mouths frozen in screams.

The memories of the crash came flooding back, and he felt a wave of nausea wash over him as he realized he was one of the few survivors. He slowly lifted his head again, this time managing to prop himself up on his elbows, and surveyed the devastation around him. As he took in the scene, he noticed a figure stumbling towards him, covered in dust and blood, with a look of utter despair etched on their face. The figure collapsed beside him, and he saw that it was a woman, her eyes vacant and her breathing labored. He reached out a shaky hand and gently touched her shoulder, trying to comfort her, but she didn't respond.

Her eyes flickered open, and she gazed up at him with a mixture of confusion and fear, her pupils dilated from whatever horrors she had witnessed. He tried to speak, but she shook her head, her hand rising to her mouth as if to stifle a scream. The woman's gaze drifted away, and she began to mutter something incoherent, her words lost in a sob that shook her entire body.

As he knelt beside her, his heart heavy with concern, she suddenly grasped his arm, her grip like a vice, and whispered "No...no...it can't be...he's dead...he's really dead..." Her eyes, still wild and unfocused, locked onto his, pleading for him to understand, to believe her, as the sobs wracked her body and tears streamed down her face.

"Who's dead?" he asked, his voice low and urgent, trying to keep his tone calm despite the growing sense of unease that was spreading through his chest. "Who's really dead?" he repeated, his eyes scanning her face, searching for some sign of what was happening, what she was trying to tell him.
"Your father," she whispered, her voice barely audible over the sound of her own ragged breathing. "He's been dead for hours. I'm so sorry, I didn't know what else to do."
